</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[813,1458,215,345]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
DIAGNOSIS. — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pleijel" authorityYear="1998" box="[970,1095,215,239]" class="Polychaeta" family="Hesionidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Annelida" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Psamathinae">Psamathinae</taxonomicName>
with two lateral antennae, without median antenna; no frontal tubercle; eyes present; nuchal organs separate; palpostyles ovoid, as long as palpophores; 8 pairs of tentacular cirri; without notochaetae; neurochaetae with simple and compound falcigers; pharynx without jaws, with marginal papillae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[813,1457,368,525]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
DISTRIBUTION. — The species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Johnston" authorityYear="1836" box="[1148,1237,368,392]" class="Polychaeta" family="Hesionidae" genus="Psamathe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1148,1237,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Psamathe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are only known from temperate localities in the Atlantic and Pacific and from the Antarctic, in shallow water, rocky or mixed bottoms. A new species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Salazar-Vallejo, 2022" authorityName="Salazar-Vallejo" authorityYear="2022" box="[814,904,448,472]" class="Polychaeta" family="Hesionidae" genus="Psamathe" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="charpyi" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis box="[814,904,448,472]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">P. charpyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[910,965,448,471]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, is described from the Eastern tropical Pacific. The confusion in the identification of the species and their rarity might explain these sporadic records.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
